Insight 💡

The most powerful insight from this analysis is that EV charging demand is highly concentrated in specific locations, times, and user behaviors rather than being evenly distributed across all garages.

A small number of garages (Bl2, AsO2, and UT9) account for the majority of shared charger users, while peak demand consistently happens during late afternoons to early evenings (3 PM – 7 PM), especially on Sundays. At the same time, a few users keep chargers occupied for 10–17 hours on average, significantly reducing access for others.

Why This Matters

This means the real problem may not simply be “not enough chargers,” but rather inefficient charger allocation and poor turnover management.

Instead of installing chargers everywhere, apartment managers can gain faster and cheaper improvements by:

* Expanding chargers only in high-demand garages
* Managing peak-hour access with reservations
* Introducing charging time limits or idle fees
* Encouraging off-peak charging behavior

Strategic Conclusion

Smart management of charger usage could solve a large portion of access problems without major infrastructure spending. This turns charging stations from a hardware problem into a data-driven operations opportunity.
